  "footnotes": [
    "T (Tangier): northern tip including Ceuta (Portuguese 1415, Spanish 1640–present), Tangier itself was an International Zone (1923–1956) and briefly British (1661–1684)",
    "N (Rif): Mediterranean coast and Rif mountains; Salihids of Nakur were the first Berber dynasty here after the Islamic conquest; this zone formed Spain's northern protectorate (1912–1956)",
    "C (Atlantic): Casablanca–Rabat corridor; Barghawata was a heretical Berber confederation here (744–1058) with their own Quran; became the French Protectorate heartland",
    "F (Fes): founded by Idris II (808 CE) as Morocco's spiritual and intellectual capital; remained the seat of power under Idrisids, Marinids (Fes el-Bali is their legacy), and Alawites",
    "M (Marrakesh): founded 1062 by Almoravids as their capital; Almohads and Saadians also used it; alternates with Fes as Morocco's capital throughout history",
    "A (Atlas): High Atlas Berber (Masmuda) origin of the Almohad movement; largely autonomous throughout history under Berber tribal confederations",
    "S (Tafilalet / Sijilmasa): eastern oasis corridor; Midraris founded Sijilmasa (757–976), an early trans-Saharan gold trade hub; Tafilalet is the Alawite dynasty's ancestral homeland",
    "WS (Western Sahara): Almoravids originated from the Sanhaja of this zone; contested between Morocco and SADR (Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic) since Spanish withdrawal (1975–76)"
  ]
